Looking at the test method `testEmpty1256`, I can see it expects an empty JSON `{}` when serializing an `Issue1256Bean()` with `NON_ABSENT` inclusion. The `Issue1256Bean` contains two `AtomicReference<Object>` fields with empty constructor values.

Let me look more closely at the relevant part of the PropertyBuilder where the bug likely occurs. The bug seems to be related to how `NON_ABSENT` inclusion works with `AtomicReference` types. From the test, we see:

```java
static class Issue1256Bean {
    @JsonSerialize(as=AtomicReference.class)
    public Object a = new AtomicReference<Object>();  // Empty AtomicReference
    public AtomicReference<Object> b = new AtomicReference<Object>();  // Empty AtomicReference
}

@Test
public void testEmpty1256() throws Exception {
    ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
    mapper.setSerializationInclusion(JsonInclude.Include.NON_ABSENT); // This should exclude empty AtomicReferences

    String json = mapper.writeValueAsString(new Issue1256Bean());
    assertEquals("{}", json);  // Expects empty JSON, but probably gets both fields
}
```

The problem is in the PropertyBuilder around the `NON_ABSENT` handling code. Let me look closely at the switch statement:

Looking at the code, I can see the issue. In the `NON_ABSENT` case:

```java
case NON_ABSENT: // new with 2.6, to support Guava/JDK8 Optionals
    // always suppress nulls
    suppressNulls = true;
    // and for referential types, also "empty", which in their case means "absent"
    if (declaredType.isReferenceType()) {
        valueToSuppress = BeanPropertyWriter.MARKER_FOR_EMPTY;
    }
    break;
```

The problem is that `AtomicReference` is not being recognized as a referential type by `declaredType.isReferenceType()`, so the `NON_ABSENT` exclusion is not working properly for `AtomicReference` objects.

Let me check what constitutes a reference type in Jackson:

